FireRed and LeafGreen Trainer Tower

The FireRed and LeafGreen Trainer Tower, located in the map area also called Trainer Tower north of Seven Island, is a battle facility accessible only in FireRed and LeafGreen. In this facility, Trainers can take up to six Pokémon into a series of battles separated by floor, with a total of eight floors. This facility was originally intended to be used with e-Reader cards; scanning e-Reader cards would change the enemy Trainers and Pokémon that the player would fight on each floor of the tower. As the e-Reader did not receive much support outside of Japan, the ability to use e-Reader cards was removed from international releases of FireRed and LeafGreen, and the player instead fights predetermined Trainers based on some of the data provided by the original e-Reader cards.

Battle Mechanics

In this facility, items can be used outside battle, and the player can actually return to the entrance of the tower in order to heal their Pokémon during the challenge. The catch is that the player is rewarded an item for completing the tower within a certain time limit; returning to heal Pokémon will make this time limit harder to maintain.
When the facility is first accessed, the record time for every mode is 59:99.99. If the player can beat this time, they will receive the reward, and the time taken to beat the challenge will become the new record. After that, the player will need to beat the new record time to receive the item again.

No EXP or prize money is gained for battles fought in the Trainer Tower. The level of all of the opposing Pokémon will match the level of the player's highest-leveled Pokémon. The enemy Pokémon will always have predetermined EVs, IVs, and movesets regardless of their level.

The moves Thief, Covet, and Trick will fail here.

Return, Frustration, and Hidden Power all have maximum power.

Mode Mechanics

In all versions of the game, there are three types of floor that the player can encounter:

  • Single Mode: A single trainer occupies the floor. They have two Pokémon.
  • Double Mode: Two trainers occupy the floor. They are fought in a Double Battle. They have two Pokémon.
  • Knockout Mode: Three trainers occupy the floor. They are positioned in such a way that the player will need to fight them one after the other. They each have one Pokémon.

In the Japanese versions of FireRed and LeafGreen, which mode a given floor uses is dependent on the cards scanned with the e-Reader; more information about the e-Reader mechanics is given below.

In international versions of FireRed and LeafGreen, entering the Trainer Tower allows the player to choose which of four modes to challenge: the three shown above, and a fourth, "Mixed Mode", which consists of three Single Mode floors, three Double Mode floors, and two Knockout Mode floors. Each mode choice contains a static set of Trainers that the player will fight.

Data

The rest of the page contains three sections: one containing the international releases' static Trainer data; one containing the Japanese releases' default Trainers (which occupy only four floors instead of eight), and one containing all the known e-Reader card data for enemy Trainers. As the enemy Pokémon can be any level, their IVs and EVs are given instead of a stat. To calculate their stats, you can use a calculator such as Pokémon Showdown's; select "ADV" as the generation.

e-Reader Trainer Data

e-Reader cards can only be scanned in the Japanese releases of FireRed and LeafGreen. Scanning e-Reader cards replaces the default trainers with data for other trainers, dependent on which card is scanned. Although the default Trainer Tower in Japanese releases is only four floors, scanning e-Reader cards allows for up to eight floors.

Each card contains data for one mode type: Single, Double, or Knockout. Single cards contain one trainer, Double cards contain two and Knockout cards contain 3. Scanning e-Reader cards effectively causes the Trainer Tower to work similarly to the international releases' Knockout Mode, where different floors can have different modes.

Each Trainer additionally has an item associated with them. Defeating the Trainer Tower will give the player a reward that corresponds to the item associated with the Trainer that the player fought on the first floor. Due to a relative lack of data, I'm unsure if the item can only be obtained if the Trainer Tower is defeated within a time limit, as is the case with the international releases.

Each Trainer has a party with six Pokémon, even though any individual Trainer fought in the Tower will only have one or two Pokémon. The Trainer Tower is set up to choose an appropriate number of Pokémon depending on which floor the Trainer is fought on. The party slots (corresponding to the Number column in the below tables) selected on each floor are as follows:

Single Mode:

  • 1F: 1, 3
  • 2F: 2, 4
  • 3F: 3, 5
  • 4F: 4, 6
  • 5F: 5, 2
  • 6F: 6, 3
  • 7F: 1, 4
  • 8F: 2, 5

Double Mode:

  • 1F: 1, 2
  • 2F: 2, 4
  • 3F: 3, 1
  • 4F: 4, 5
  • 5F: 5, 3
  • 6F: 6, 3
  • 7F: 1, 4
  • 8F: 2, 6

Knockout Mode:

  • 1F: 1, 3, 5
  • 2F: 2, 4, 6
  • 3F: 3, 4, 2
  • 4F: 4, 5, 1
  • 5F: 5, 2, 3
  • 6F: 6, 1, 4
  • 7F: 1, 6, 3
  • 8F: 2, 5, 6

For example, a Double Battle fought on Floor 7 will choose the 1st Pokémon from the 1st Trainer on the card, and the 4th Pokémon from the 2nd Trainer on the card.
This is, incidentally, the reason why Picnicker シホリ, who is fought as the 2nd Trainer in a Knockout Mode floor on the 3rd floor of the default Tower, uses a Venomoth: the Venomoth is technically in her party as the 4th Pokémon, and on 7F, the second Trainer fought uses their 4th Pokémon.

In addition to the cards listed below, there are four other cards, known simply as "D1-D4" in the source I used for these, which will restore the Tower to its default Trainer layout. There are also promotional cards (called Promo P1, Promo N1, Promo N2, Promo N3, and Promo N4) that can be scanned. Due to a lack of data, the movesets, natures, Abilities, and stats of these cards' Pokémon are unknown. If I am able to find more data about these, I will update the page accordingly. The promotional cards' known data is listed at the bottom of the page.
